                                                                                                                                    Starwood set to widen reach

   GARIMA SINGH-NEOGY
        ROOM FOR MORE
   
	New Delhi, Jan. 1: The US-based hospitality chain Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide will open more hotels mdash; under the Westin and Aloft brands mdash; in India. 
 
	The company plans to open Westin hotels in Calcutta, Hyderabad and Pune. Sources could not confirm whether Starwood would enter into local partnerships to set up these properties or would do it on its own.
 
	For the Aloft brand, Starwood has joined hands with Urbanedge Hotels, which is a joint venture between Citigroup Property Investors and Auromatrix Hotels.
 
	The company is building three Westin properties in Bangalore, Sohna and Gurgaon, taking the total number of Westin hotels in the country to six. For these hotels it has tied up with the Delhi-based Vatika group. 
 
	While the hotel in Calcutta will be launched in 2010, the properties in Hyderabad and Pune will open in 2008 and 2009, respectively.
 
	Brian McGuinness, vice-president of Aloft and Element hotels, said the first two Aloft hotels would be Bangalore and Chennai. 
 
	Element is another brand of Starwood.
 
	Were thrilled to bring a bold new lodging alternative to the land for all seasons, he added.
 
	The Aloft Bangalore will be a 170-room hotel with a large restaurant and more than 8,500 square feet of meeting space. The Aloft Chennai will have around 140 guest rooms, over 5,000 square feet of meeting space and a restaurant. It will be located on the Old Mahabalipuram Road. Both properties will start operating in 2010. 
 
	Developers in India have expressed keen interest in Aloft hotels, particularly in newly developing sub-markets in both major urban centres and secondary cities, said Miguel Ko, president mdash; Asia Pacific, Starwood Hotels amp; Resorts Worldwide. 
                                                            
